## Set up Nginx as a Reverse Proxy

### 1. Detect the deployment context
- Ask (or detect from existing config) whether Nginx runs:
  - **Natively on Linux** (Ubuntu/Debian systemd service) — most common for VPS deployments
  - **Inside Docker Compose** — Nginx as a container alongside the app container
- The config syntax is identical; only the file locations and reload commands differ.

### 2. Install Nginx (native)
```bash
sudo apt update && sudo apt install -y nginx
sudo systemctl enable nginx && sudo systemctl start nginx
nginx -v  # Verify — target 1.18+
```
- IMPORTANT: Do NOT install from default Ubuntu repos on older distros — they ship Nginx 1.14. Add the official Nginx apt repo for 1.24+.

### 3. Create a server block (virtual host)
- Create `/etc/nginx/sites-available/myapp`:
```nginx
server {
    listen 80;
    listen [::]:80;
    server_name example.com www.example.com;

    # Redirect all HTTP to HTTPS (add after SSL is configured)
    return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
}

server {
    listen 443 ssl;
    listen [::]:443 ssl;
    server_name example.com www.example.com;

    # SSL certificates (filled in by Certbot)
    ssl_certificate     /etc/letsencrypt/live/example.com/fullchain.pem;
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/example.com/privkey.pem;
    include             /etc/letsencrypt/options-ssl-nginx.conf;
    ssl_dhparam         /etc/letsencrypt/ssl-dhparams.pem;

    # Proxy to your app
    location / {
        proxy_pass         http://127.0.0.1:3000;
        proxy_http_version 1.1;
        proxy_set_header   Upgrade $http_upgrade;
        proxy_set_header   Connection 'upgrade';
        proxy_set_header   Host $host;
        proxy_set_header   X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header   X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header   X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
        proxy_cache_bypass $http_upgrade;
    }
}
```
- Enable: `sudo ln -s /etc/nginx/sites-available/myapp /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/`
- IMPORTANT: Always use `proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme` — required by Next.js and Express to detect HTTPS correctly.

### 4. Add gzip compression
- Add inside the `server` block (or in `/etc/nginx/nginx.conf` `http` block for global effect):
```nginx
gzip on;
gzip_vary on;
gzip_proxied any;
gzip_comp_level 6;
gzip_types text/plain text/css text/xml text/javascript
           application/json application/javascript application/xml+rss
           application/atom+xml image/svg+xml;
```
- IMPORTANT: Do NOT enable `gzip` for images (jpeg/png/webp) — they are already compressed and gzip will make them larger.

### 5. Add security headers
```nginx
add_header X-Frame-Options           "SAMEORIGIN" always;
add_header X-Content-Type-Options    "nosniff" always;
add_header Referrer-Policy           "strict-origin-when-cross-origin" always;
add_header Permissions-Policy        "geolocation=(), microphone=()" always;
add_header Strict-Transport-Security "max-age=63072000; includeSubDomains; preload" always;
```
- Add these inside the `server {}` block for the HTTPS vhost.
- IMPORTANT: Only set `Strict-Transport-Security` on the HTTPS server block — never on the HTTP redirect block.

### 6. Add rate limiting
- In `/etc/nginx/nginx.conf`, inside the `http {}` block, define a zone:
```nginx
limit_req_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=api:10m rate=10r/s;
```
- Apply in the server block for API routes:
```nginx
location /api/ {
    limit_req zone=api burst=20 nodelay;
    proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:3000;
    # ... other proxy_set_header directives
}
```
- `burst=20` allows short spikes; `nodelay` serves burst requests immediately instead of queuing.

### 7. Obtain SSL certificate with Certbot
```bash
sudo apt install -y certbot python3-certbot-nginx
sudo certbot --nginx -d example.com -d www.example.com
```
- Certbot automatically edits your Nginx config with certificate paths.
- Certbot installs a systemd timer for auto-renewal. Verify: `sudo systemctl status certbot.timer`
- Test renewal: `sudo certbot renew --dry-run`
- IMPORTANT: Port 80 must be open and Nginx must be running before running certbot.

### 8. Validate and reload Nginx
```bash
sudo nginx -t          # Always validate before reloading
sudo systemctl reload nginx
```
- NEVER run `nginx -s reload` or `systemctl restart nginx` without running `nginx -t` first — a syntax error will bring down the server.

### 9. Docker Compose setup (alternative to native)
- Create `nginx/nginx.conf` in your repo:
```nginx
events { worker_connections 1024; }

http {
    gzip on;
    gzip_types text/plain application/json application/javascript text/css;

    upstream app {
        server app:3000;  # 'app' is the Docker Compose service name
    }

    server {
        listen 80;
        server_name _;

        location / {
            proxy_pass         http://app;
            proxy_http_version 1.1;
            proxy_set_header   Upgrade $http_upgrade;
            proxy_set_header   Connection 'upgrade';
            proxy_set_header   Host $host;
            proxy_set_header   X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
            proxy_cache_bypass $http_upgrade;
        }
    }
}
```
- Add to `docker-compose.yml`:
```yaml
services:
  app:
    build: .
    expose:
      - "3000"   # Exposed only within Docker network, not to host

  nginx:
    image: nginx:1.25-alpine
    ports:
      - "80:80"
      - "443:443"
    volumes:
      - ./nginx/nginx.conf:/etc/nginx/nginx.conf:ro
      - ./nginx/certs:/etc/nginx/certs:ro   # Mount SSL certs
    depends_on:
      - app
```
- IMPORTANT: Use `expose` (not `ports`) for the app service — it should not be directly reachable from outside Docker.

### 10. WebSocket support
- WebSockets require the `Upgrade` and `Connection` headers to be proxied:
```nginx
location /socket.io/ {
    proxy_pass         http://127.0.0.1:3000;
    proxy_http_version 1.1;
    proxy_set_header   Upgrade $http_upgrade;
    proxy_set_header   Connection "upgrade";
    proxy_read_timeout 86400;   # Keep connection open for 24h
}
```
- IMPORTANT: Use a separate `location` block for WebSocket paths — the `Connection 'upgrade'` header in the main block can break non-WebSocket requests in some Nginx versions.

### 11. Serve static Next.js files directly from Nginx (performance)
```nginx
location /_next/static/ {
    alias /var/www/myapp/.next/static/;
    expires 1y;
    add_header Cache-Control "public, immutable";
}

location /public/ {
    alias /var/www/myapp/public/;
    expires 30d;
}
```
- This bypasses Node.js for static assets, significantly reducing server load.

### Common errors & fixes
- **`nginx: [emerg] unknown directive "ssl"`** — Nginx was compiled without SSL module. Use the mainline or official PPA package, not the distro default.
- **`502 Bad Gateway`** — Your app is not running on the proxied port, or the upstream address is wrong. Check `systemctl status myapp` and verify the port.
- **`413 Request Entity Too Large`** — Nginx default max body is 1MB. Add `client_max_body_size 10M;` in the server block.
- **`upstream timed out (110: Connection timed out)`** — App is slow or crashed. Increase `proxy_read_timeout 120s;` or fix the app.
- **Certbot: `Problem binding to port 80`** — Nginx is using port 80. Either stop Nginx first (`--standalone` mode) or use `--nginx` mode which patches config automatically.
- **HTTPS HSTS stuck on HTTP** — You set HSTS on the HTTP block by mistake. Move it to the HTTPS `server {}` block only.
- **WebSocket disconnects after 60s** — Nginx default `proxy_read_timeout` is 60s. Set `proxy_read_timeout 86400;` for WebSocket locations.
- **`client_header_buffer_size` warnings** — Large cookies/auth tokens. Add `large_client_header_buffers 4 16k;` in the `http` block.

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT expose the app port (3000) directly to the internet — it bypasses Nginx and loses all security/rate-limiting benefits.
- Do NOT skip `nginx -t` before reload — a config error with `systemctl restart` will bring down the entire server.
- Do NOT use `worker_processes auto;` in Docker containers without setting CPU limits — it reads the host CPU count, not the container limit.
- Do NOT set `HSTS` headers on the HTTP (port 80) server block — HSTS is only meaningful over HTTPS.
- Do NOT point SSL certificate paths before running Certbot — Nginx will fail to start.
- Do NOT use `proxy_pass http://localhost:3000` in Docker Compose — `localhost` inside the Nginx container refers to the Nginx container itself, not the app container. Use the service name.
- Do NOT disable `access_log` in production — logs are essential for debugging and security incident investigation.
- Do NOT run Nginx as root inside Docker — use `USER nginx` or the official nginx image which already drops privileges.
